</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>    (<span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;8mdash&#34;</span>   <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;—&#34;</span>)
</span></span><span style="display:flex;"><span>    (<span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;8ndash&#34;</span>   <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;–&#34;</span>)))
</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Just after you type an abbreviation following by either SPC or any
punctuation symbol it is replaced by the corresponding character.</p>
<p>Of course, I&rsquo;ve compiled this setup from various sources, mostly from
the <a href="https://impaktor.gitlab.io/dot_emacs.html#org87d6718">Impaktor&rsquo;s article</a>
with some additions.</p>
<p>It&rsquo;s also worth to read the <a href="http://xahlee.info/emacs/emacs/emacs_abbrev_mode_tutorial.html">Xah Lee&rsquo;s article</a>
for more examples of how to use <strong>abbrev</strong> mode in your daily Emacs
life.</p>
<p>Happy abbreving.</p>